	<entry>
		<title type="html">@abraxas3d @tnt Just realized that for the DCI, if the SNR is good, a UE can often use the wrong number of CCEs to try to decode a DCI and still succeed, as long as it uses the correct starting point for the CCE allocation. Probably this reduces the number of decoding attempts needed in practice</title>
		<published>2022-06-26T16:35:23+00:00</published>
		<updated>2022-06-26T16:35:23+00:00</updated>
		<id>https://twitter.com/ea4gpz/status/1541097804617097217</id>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://twitter.com/ea4gpz/status/1541097804617097217"/>
		<author><name>Daniel Estévez (@ea4gpz)</name></author>
		<content type="html">&lt;div style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: top;"&gt;
	&lt;a href="https://twitter.com/ea4gpz"&gt;
&lt;img
	style="align:top; width:75px; border:1px solid black;"
	alt="ea4gpz"
	src="https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1178008371225595905/1gtBHxvG_normal.jpg"
	title="Daniel Estévez" /&gt;
&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style="display: inline-block; vertical-align: top;"&gt;
	&lt;blockquote&gt;@abraxas3d @tnt Just realized that for the DCI, if the SNR is good, a UE can often use the wrong number of CCEs to try to decode a DCI and still succeed, as long as it uses the correct starting point for the CCE allocation. Probably this reduces the number of decoding attempts needed in practice&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style="display: block; vertical-align: top;"&gt;
	&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</content>
		
		
		
	</entry>

